  "prompt": "How long can I stay outside the UK as a dependant of the tier2 visa?",
  "response": "As a dependant of a Tier 2 (now Skilled Worker) visa holder, there's **no specific limit** on the amount of time you can spend outside the UK.  However, there are crucial considerations to ensure you maintain your visa validity and eventual eligibility for Indefinite Leave to Remain (ILR):\n\n*   **Maintaining the Main Visa Holder's Status:** Your visa is dependent on the main visa holder (your partner/parent). If the main visa holder's visa is curtailed, revoked, or they switch to a different visa type that doesn't allow dependants, your visa will also be affected.\n\n*   **Continuity of Residence for ILR:**  To qualify for ILR, you generally need to meet continuous residence requirements in the UK.  Spending significant periods outside the UK can break this continuity.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **General Absence Rule:**  While there isn't a rule *explicitly* preventing long absences, Home Office guidance indicates that absences of **more than 180 days in any 12-month period** can negatively impact your ILR application. These absences must be counted cumulatively, not individually.\n\n*   **Why the 180-Day Rule Matters:** The Home Office assesses whether you have made the UK your main home.  Prolonged absences raise doubts about whether you genuinely intend to settle in the UK.\n\n*   **Absences and Extensions:**  While not directly impacting visa extensions, repeated and lengthy absences could raise questions during future extension applications about your genuine intention to reside in the UK.\n\n*   **Important Considerations:**\n    *   **Keep Evidence:**  Maintain records that demonstrate your ties to the UK, such as:\n        *   Bank statements showing UK transactions.\n        *   Utility bills in your name at a UK address.\n        *   Council tax bills.\n        *   Letters from employers (if applicable).\n        *   Evidence of children's schooling in the UK (if applicable).\n        *   Medical records showing regular treatment in the UK.\n        *   Evidence of property ownership/rental agreements.\n\n    *   **Justification for Absences:** If you do exceed the 180-day limit, be prepared to provide a credible and compelling reason for your absences. Acceptable reasons might include:\n        *   Serious illness of a close family member abroad requiring your care.\n        *   Overseas work assignments related to the main visa holder's job (especially if you accompanied them).\n        *   Study abroad programs.\n        *   Significant and unavoidable family commitments.\n\n    *   **Accompanying the Main Visa Holder:** If the main visa holder is required to work outside the UK for an extended period, it's generally better for the whole family to go together and return together to maintain stronger ties to the UK.\n\n    *   **Seek Professional Advice:**  If you have complex circumstances or anticipate frequent or lengthy absences, it's highly recommended to consult with an immigration lawyer.  They can assess your situation, provide tailored advice, and help you navigate the ILR application process.\n\n**In summary:**\n\nWhile there's no strict \"days out of the UK\" limit for Tier 2/Skilled Worker dependants, staying within the 180-day absence rule per 12-month period is generally advisable to avoid issues with ILR.  Document all absences and maintain strong ties to the UK. When in doubt, seek professional legal advice.\n\n**Disclaimer:**  I am an AI chatbot and cannot provide immigration advice.  This information is for general guidance only and should not be considered a substitute for professional legal advice. Always consult with a qualified immigration lawyer for advice specific to your situation.\n",
